maize-292: kill -0 (process-existence check) is honestly unsupported, not faked.

Upstream file/function: kill.c, main().
Why: quesOS's do_kill (os/quesos/quesos.c) rejects any signal outside 1..31, so the
stock kill -0 pid / kill 0 pid existence check (POSIX: send signal 0, no real
signal delivered, success/failure reflects whether the pid exists) now returns
EINVAL unconditionally instead of the correct existence-check result. Sending a
real, state-mutating signal (e.g. SIGCONT) as a substitute would be worse than the
honest gap, so this overlay makes the deviation explicit: sig == 0 prints a clear
"process-existence check is not supported on this platform" message and returns
the same nonzero status stock kill -0 would return on failure. Every other signal
(1-31, the whole sigs[] table minus its "0" entry) is unaffected and works exactly
as upstream. A second, unrelated fix rides the same overlay: kill.c calls kill()
without including <unistd.h> (POSIX declares kill() in <signal.h>; the Maize RT
declares it only in <unistd.h>, matching decision 9695's stdin-only RT-change
scope for this card, so the fix lands here in the userland patch instead of
widening signal.h).
diff --git a/kill.c b/kill.c
index e69de29..1111111 100644
--- a/kill.c
+++ b/kill.c
@@ -7,6 +7,7 @@
 #include <stdio.h>
 #include <string.h>
 #include <strings.h>
+#include <unistd.h>

 #include "util.h"

@@ -120,6 +121,16 @@

 	for (; *argv; argc--, argv++) {
 		pid = estrtonum(*argv, INT_MIN, INT_MAX);
+		if (sig == 0) {
+			/* maize-292: quesOS's do_kill rejects sig outside 1..31, so the
+			 * POSIX existence-check idiom (kill -0 / kill 0) cannot be honored
+			 * here; sending a real signal as a substitute would mutate process
+			 * state, so this says so plainly instead of the misleading stock
+			 * "Invalid argument" text. Every signal 1-31 is unaffected. */
+			weprintf("kill %d: process-existence check (signal 0) is not supported on this platform\n", pid);
+			ret = 1;
+			continue;
+		}
 		if (kill(pid, sig) < 0) {
 			weprintf("kill %d:", pid);
 			ret = 1;
